Text: Back on the episode of 'greyhound project progress' ðŸ•- things have been aÂ little stagnant in terms of the state of the project.
Last week, I had personal goals to complete the population of our database with all the historical results data.
Did I achieve that, you ask?
Not exactly.
A series of events that lead to that not happening, could have been prevented if I had been better prepared or knowledgable.
The state of the project itself is in-cohesive.
Our team dynamic at the moment, is also in-cohesive.
If I am honest - I may have been too optimistic that I could have achieved that goal.
Last week, I estimated that it would take approximately 2.5 hours to populate the 'dog' table of our MySQL database.
However, I was unaware of something called 'ethical web scraping'.
Although the 'robots.txt' had allowed me to scrape from the greyhound website, ethically scraping meant being mindful of not overloading the websites server.
After re-calculation, scraping for that one table would take me ~16 hours.
Do not get me wrong, the duration itself did not scare me, but, what I was afraid of came under the umbrella of three things:
1) Whether my script was going to work:  the thought of scraping for 16 consecutive hours worried me, because what if for whatever reason - the script or connection crashes.
I also had thousands of other webpages to scrape from for the other tables.
2) Would the data portray its true form:  I was not 100% sure that the script would scrape the data properly and maintain its true form.
What if I had been scraping thousands of pages with the wrong data format
and 3) I was not actually ethically scraping:  what if their website blocks access from my local machine and I can no longer scrape from the website.
Clearly, lack of experience meant no sense of intuition.
I simply could not trust that this could work.

For the entirety of this week, I had it tweaking my script to mirror the columns on the MySQL database and spending afternoons thinking about the best way to approach the scraping and querying into the database with as low risk as possible.
Upon discussion with some of my close friends - they suggested that I perhaps start by scraping a small workable sample.
This solves the problem of giving my team mates with something to work with, testing my script in parallel and scraping and importing into MySQL with low risk.
A simple art of doing one thing at a time.
In the future, I hope that these experience will give me the confidence to perhaps trust my intuition more and perhaps plan my work based on undergoing smaller increments so that eases my anxiety.
For now, I will at the very least trust the productivity framework of doing things one at a time.
As I had mentioned earlier - the state of the project is simply a mess.
I fear that we may not have something to deliver for our client.
So far, we haveÂ someÂ workable data and perhaps a framework design of the webpage.
I had a one-on-one meeting with Kevin (our client) on Thursday to ask a simple question in relation to my portion of the project.
What I discover instead is that we have only partially understood our clients needs.
Of course, the automation aspect ties in with getting the data, but it was also about how we displayed the data (specific instructions found on the handout he had given us).
To put it simply - a few averages of winner's time needed to be calculated for each distance, each class and each track.
The top 5%, 10% and 20% dogs will be colour coded accordingly.
The rest will remain uncoloured and insignificant.

The colour coding will ultimately signify whether a dog is worth betting on (this may not make sense as there are other instructions in between, but I am looking at this at a totally practical point of view).
I describe to my teammates of this aspect - and some of them had simply refused to acknowledge this gap.
Panic sets in because I had felt an immense amount of pressure to deliver this myself.
I cannot seem to find a beam from my team to lean on - a metaphor for feeling unsupported I suppose.
For now,Â  in an attempt to stress less about the project, I have decided that I will carry through 'doing one thing at a time' - and hope that I can at least partially cater to our clients needs.
One thing I wanted to improve on with these projects are my people skills.
I am finding it difficult to navigate and overcome these obstacles.
Obviously, issues in a group project are not uncommon, but I also believe that things can get better - I just don't know how to encourage positive behaviour and habits.
The group at current embodies conflict and tension, low engagement, non delivering and poor change management.
To be transparent - there are some conflict amongst ourselves.
Lack of individual engagement and non delivering of tasks and attitudes has evidently brought the spirit of the whole team down.
Change is also evidently difficult for some of my team members.
I've been having conflicting feelings on what to do about our team problems to help the project move forward.
Seems as though communication alone is not going to fix our team dynamic - there is also an aspect of listening that needs to be worked on.
To help make light of this situation - I am attempting to take responsibility for my own approach in this project.
Upon vigorous reflection yesterday, I am deciding to fully commit myself to the project and do the best that I can for the project and client - despite the lack of support.
It has been difficult - but to me it is also an important lesson to learning how to navigate myself in a group project such as this.
I think what would definitely help next time is if we perhaps had a team leader to help put things into perspective and help communicate the bigger picture.
Perhaps, a team leader would allow for efficient project management and team management.
For now, my role in the project has taken a slight change.
Riri was doing her own 'alternative solution' for our project because I think she might have misunderstood the projects tasks at hand.

For one of our 'to-do' tasks, we discussed perhaps delivering a 'write-up' of instructions for Kevin, of how to use Excel for web scraping, just so we at least gave him something valuable at the end of the project (incase our project was incomplete).
She instead decided to do her own side project and undergo some web scraping and portraying data on HTML.
She felt that the initial task (Excel instruction writeup) was 'restricting her learning'.
For now, Yoko has offered to undergo that task.

Due to the state of the project - I thought that I would rather Riri contribute directly to the project, rather than splitting off and doing her own thing - so I suggested that she perhaps take over my web scraping task since she was doing so already.
For now, she has agreed.
This took some weight off my shoulders because I had a few other things I had planned to do which will be my project goals for next week: .
a) Research the best way to display the data tables on the webpage based on the information we plan to display.
This involves also researching what tools to use.
b) Create a low fidelity prototype for Yoko to continue implementing the HTML aspect,Â
c) Finish altering the ERD diagram and send to Susu (which won't be much different) andÂ
d) Based on the one-on-one meeting Kevin and I had, I will initiate the implementation of that script.
Let's see how next week goes!
